segments.text: So that first semester went well, and your grades came out okay?
About a three, four.
Three, four.
Did you have a goal that you were shooting for?
That, I mean, I didn't really, I knew I wanted to do well, but I knew I didn't want to, I didn't want my only thing at A&M to be my grades.
I knew that.
As you began to try to look further into the future, who did you turn to for advice?
A man named Dr. Ben Welch.
I don't know if you've heard his name at all.
At the time he was in charge of the fellows program in the School of Business.
He is Aggie Men's Club advisor.
An absolutely amazing man.
Probably the man in which I've learned most of at this, since I've been here.
Dr. Welch.
What made him a good advisor?

his genuine love of A&M and genuine love of the group in which I was involved in I mean like he loves Aggie Men's Club and he loves Texas A&M and it was just very obvious that he did that and he was just he's a very caring individual he takes the time to give you a hug he takes the time to see how you're doing which is great and so it was just very easy to talk to him did
While you were getting very much involved and attached, were you aware of other freshmen who were just kind of getting left out?
I was.
My roommate was one of them.
Is that right?
My roommate was one of them.
What could have been done in hindsight?
What could I have done or what could they have done?
What could A&M have done or what could they have done?
I think a big part of my roommate was the fact that he played football, which is such a big time commitment, and he just didn't enjoy it.
He just wasn't enjoying himself because walk-ons don't get a fair shake at the school.
And so he was getting really frustrated with the fact that he was going out there four hours a day and nothing was really coming of it.
But as far as I think...
He didn't even go to MSC open house.
He didn't try.
He didn't put forth the effort.
And at A&M, you have to put forth the effort a little bit if it's going to get.
I mean, it's just like anything else.
And so him not putting forth the effort kind of doomed him for the rest of it.
And he ended up transferring after his freshman year.
All right.
But you stayed the whole semester, the whole year in Cane.
I did.
As you go home Christmas, you feel good about the first semester.
I do.
I feel very good about the first semester.
Now, what does an Aggie do for four weeks in the semester break?
Hang out with high school friends and go skiing.
I remember I went skiing.
I went skiing with some of my high school friends actually.
and then just hung out with them.
And did you tell them anything about A&M?
Oh, yeah, if they had listened.
But a lot of them wouldn't listen.
There was, out of the 73 people that graduated from my high school, 21 of them came to A&M.
Really?
So...
So your second semester you dug in more deeply and did you start looking around for a specific major?
A little bit I did.
I had heard that the College of Business was starting to put requirements on GPA requirements, which I was fine just as far as that goes.
But I started looking towards business simply because I enjoyed history a lot.
I remember talking to my parents about history.
I had a great, great class.
Probably one of the better classes I've taken.
It was History 106.
Its name was Arnie Kramer.
Loved that class.
Loved Mr. Kramer.
We ended up becoming relatively good friends.
I stopped by his office every once in a while.
We just became...
very close and I really enjoyed his teaching method.
I know him well, but what made him outstanding?
His love for what he was doing.

honestly it was just very obvious that he really enjoyed not only history but also teaching students about it and he took it very seriously and he rewarded students in the right way of rewarding students you know it wasn't just he didn't reward students just by going okay good job like if you came to class you got rewarded for it if you did extra credit you got rewarded for it the tests were a combination of having to know facts but also just using your mind as well
And also, he just made it fun, you know.
He threw in little, at least for me, who can't think on one subject forever.
It was a Tuesday, Thursday class, and so it was an hour and a half long.
He would throw in random stuff.
I mean, he's always big on word origins, and he's really big on that type of stuff.
And so, he would throw in stuff that would keep your interest going.
And just, I loved going by his office hours.
We always had such great conversations, and we ended up actually going to lunch a couple times, and it was just really neat.
Did you know anything about his background?
I did once the semester started progressing just as far as what he did as far as the civil rights and stuff like that.
No, I'm meaning his grandparents.
No, I don't.
One of his grandfathers or great-grandfathers was the chief rabbi in Budapest.
His father or grandfather immigrated over here, worked about eight years, goes back, says to the synagogue congregation, I'm looking for a wife.
And one of the families said, here she is.
They get married and come back to the Chicago area.
And he grew up learning to speak Magyar Yiddish English
And German.
And so, and many of his relatives were involved in the Holocaust and all like that.
Oh, yeah.
So he had firsthand experience in that.
The, in general, that freshman year, were the instructors good?
I was relatively blessed with my instructors.
I remember second semester freshman year having one that I didn't really care for.
He was my oceanography professor.
It was much like I was a number.
And he just came in, said his stuff, and then left.
He was never really at his office hours, very distant, very big on research.
And that's one thing that I kind of, I think any time you get a university professor,
A lot of them think that their main job is research rather than teaching, which I don't agree with, but I guess they're open to do whatever they want.
But that kind of frustrates me sometimes.
If you want to be a researcher, then go work for a research company.
Don't act like you're a professor.
Now, did you zero in on business eventually?
For a while.
Oh, okay.
For a while.
My major is not business.
I did zero in on business.
I became a business major beginning of my sophomore year.
Yeah, beginning of my sophomore year I became a business major.
Alright, then that second semester though you had more into student activities.
Were there any that you added that?
I didn't get in any.
Other than fish camp.
I got fish camp.
It's funny, people ask me, they're like, well, how has your college career been so successful?
Like everything you've done, it seems like you've touched his turn to gold and all this kind of stuff, just as far as the elections I've won and stuff like that.
But I've been denied more than I've been accepted at A&M to organizations.
I tried out for four organizations first semester of my freshman year, got into one.
Tried out for four more second semester, got into one.
I applied to eight my sophomore year, got into three.
So I've definitely tried stuff, but just, I mean, don't get into everything.
As you look back on those successes and lack thereof, do you think that the process was relatively fair?
Oh, definitely.
Some of the stuff kind of frustrates me.
It's kind of like a catch-22 situation.

I guess I'm a theater arts major and so I'm trying to get into theater obviously and the problem with theater is that it's kind of an inclusive group that if you don't know someone or if you aren't already in the group then they aren't going to let you do anything but you can't do anything unless you're in the group and so it's kind of a catch-22 well student government is much the same way if you don't know someone then it's very hard to get involved but yet they want to involve more people and so it's this kind of this dichotomy of mission I guess and so I guess if I could change anything it'd be a lot of that
What about the MSC and all its activities?
I didn't know about the MSC, to be honest with you.
I knew about the MSC.
I was in the MSC all the time, but I didn't know about all the organizations.
I heard about MSC Hospitality, and I heard about MSC Opus.
But other than that, I really didn't know about anything.
I didn't know about Town Hall.
I wish there was some freshman organizations that I could have gotten involved in that are here in the MSC that are housed here.
There's just a lot of stuff that I didn't know about.
I was gone for 17 years, and one of my shocks when I came back was that SCONA
is very little today.
It was one of the grandest activities on the campus.
It was big.
They were raising $40,000, $50,000 per year themselves as students in the 60s.
Wow.
Let's see.
Then did you say you eventually ended up as a theater arts major?
Yes.
When did you?
Second semester of my sophomore year.
Okay.
All right.
You finished the first year.
Your grades were okay.
What did you do that summer?
I interned at my church.
I got a job.
I got a job and went, and something that college students, many college students do, you walk through the M.I.C.
and get a gooder credit card.
So you get a credit card and you're just like, wow, this is easy to spend.
And so I racked up a, not a huge debt, but a couple hundred dollars in debt.
And I was just like, oh my gosh, can't do this.
So I went back that summer.
I interned at my church and I just paid that off.
Just had a really fun time.
I was involved in fish camp, hung out with some high school friends, really did some neat stuff.
Just as far as hanging out with my parents, went on some fun trips with some high school friends.
Like we went to New York, some friends of mine, about six of us, we went to New York and just stayed for a week.
And then just came back for fish camp.
And so that summer was really just kind of a time away, I guess.
Did you do any introspection after the first year in preparation for the second?
Oh, yeah.
What did you decide you were going to modify or change?
My involvement level in A&M.
My involvement level in my friends had been very high my freshman year just as far as pouring myself into, for instance, Aggie Men's Club and the friends that went in that.
I did some, I felt that I represented myself really well my freshman year.
And so then that summer I was, I just really was like, okay, I started thinking about the Yale leader thing again, simply because you run at the end of your sophomore year.
So that was something that was on my mind a little bit.
I hadn't decided that I was going to do it yet.
but it was on my mind.
And so I came back to school and I just got really involved with stuff.
I was living in a house off campus with some friends.
I lived with some seniors, which was really neat.
It was my best friend and myself that I made here.
We didn't know each other before we got to A&M.
He and I lived with four other seniors, graduating seniors.
So it was really neat.
to see a 22-year-old in college as an 18-year-old, you know.
As a 19-year-old, you got to see a 22-year-old, which was just such an amazing learning experience, which was really neat.
Alright, now describe the daily class, the class day routine then.
Living off campus in a house, what time did y'all get up, what time did you do this or that?
I guess it was very dependent upon what time my class started.
I really can't remember what my exact schedule was.
I remember I didn't have any 8 o'clock's my sophomore year, which is really good.

But off campus parking is obviously a hassle, so I got a bike and I got a little trailer hitch that went on my little Blazer that I could put my bike on there and I'd go and I'd park out at Reed Arena and then ride my bike all over campus.
which is great and it worked fine.
The thing that makes me laugh about it is that all these people complain about parking.
All these people complain about all this stuff.
And I'm like, it's because you're lazy.
I was like, there's always a parking spot at Reed Arena.
Always, 24 hours a day.
If you want to go park there and just get on the bus, then you're fine.
But all these people want...
parking to be right next to the classroom, which isn't going to happen.
Makes me laugh.
I think the student body is very apathetic as far as wanting to do something for themselves about problems other than just sitting around complaining.
And I've learned that this past year as far as just in the leadership role that I've been in and the committees I've been on.
I'm kind of frustrated with the student body sometimes.
Now, what would you, you'd come to the campus and stay all day?
Pretty much, just simply because, well, I'd come for at least a little bit, but I would have meetings at night, so I'd go home and I'd have to change for meetings.
But when you parked at Reed Arena, got on your bike, what did you bring with you to campus?
Just my books and my day planner and my wallet, I guess.
Backpack?
Backpack, yes, there would be a backpack.
And any stories about bike?
Oh, sure, bike collisions all the time.
I mean, they were a weekly occurrence.
They just happened.
Sometimes cars, sometimes people, but sometimes you'd try and hop a curb and not do it and you'd fall.
Ever get hurt?
Not too bad.
Not too bad.
I mean, I'd skin an knee and skin an elbow.
Bike theft, ever?
Yes, twice.
Two bikes got stolen.
Didn't get it back?
No, didn't get it back.
Didn't get it back.
Was this unusual, or did other people have the same?
Bike theft is very commonplace, yeah.
I didn't know that.
Yeah, bike theft is enormous on this campus.
Does anybody know what it is?
Does somebody else just steal it and use it?
I don't know.
I honestly don't know.
Did you ever see, think you saw it?
Yes.
Oh, yeah.
I thought I'd saw it.
I thought I'd see it, and I'd run after them, and they'd be gone.
Wow.
Alright, so you'd come, where'd you eat lunch then?
MSC, again, simply because I didn't have on-campus dining and so I just ate at Aggie Bucks.
With a group or anything?
With my friends, just with my friends that would be there.
Or I'd, yeah, I'd eat in the 12th Man a whole lot.
Alright, then in the afternoons when you had free time, where'd you go?
I'd go home.
I remember I'd work out.
I'd go to the rec center maybe.
I'd go over to another friend's house, but then I'd go home.
My house was one.
It was very big.
Turn of the century colonial house.
Plantation house out in Bryan by downtown Bryan.
You know the Kyle house?
Right across the street from the Kyle house.
It was on Finnfeather.
Well, you know how Finnfeather turns and it becomes something else?
Well, it picks up again right there.
And I lived right on that street.
And just huge house, four bedroom.
We had six guys living there.
And it was just...
So all their friends were coming over all the time.
So the house was a really neat place that we'd go to bed at 4 o'clock every day.
How did you all in that house, how did you all
divvy up the food.
Who bought what groceries?
Who cooked?
We said we each had a cabinet and so just as far as snacks and stuff goes, you're in charge of that yourself, but as milk, eggs, stuff that goes in the refrigerator, meat, that's kind of community.
And it was just kind of up to the honor of the person to go get more.
Did you cook your own?
Sometimes.
relatively everybody played to the rules?
Yeah, it was a really good thing.
One of the great things about my freshman year is we had something called family dinner, which was every Monday night we'd eat dinner together.
And it would rotate.
We had a schedule.
Either someone would cook or you'd take everyone out to dinner for the whole house.
And so it was really neat just simply because that was a weekly event in which we got together even if we were really busy and just kind of talked.
And then that fall of your sophomore year, bonfire again?
What was your task?
I lived off campus, so it was a lot harder to get involved with bonfire.
I went to cut three times, I think.
I went to father-son cut.
Where was the cut area that year?
Snook the first year, where?
It was...
I think it was Snook again, just a different part of Snook.
I remember the road where you turned off to get to it, but I don't remember how to get to that specific place.
So that's the fall of 98.
Fall of 98, yes.
Did you or any of your buddies ever talk about danger, worries about Bonfire?
Oh, sure.
At Cutside, I remember one time we got out there and it was wet that morning.
So we were cutting and a friend of mine who has never wielded an axe before got it and swung and missed right by two people's heads.
So it was plainly obvious.
For those of you working in the cut area, you all were entirely separate from the stackers.
No, you can do both.
You can do both.
Did many do both?
Most people did both.
Most people did both.
Something because stack didn't start until cutting was done.
What would be your guess as to how many people actually participated in bonfire during those years?
Cutting, stacking?
No, do you say going out once or do you say heavily involved?
No.
4,000 went once.
As far as the dedicated crew of people that would build it, 250.
And were they civilian or corps?
It was both.
What would be?
Half and half.
Half and half?
Maybe a little more civilian simply because there's more people that are civilian.
Were there any women in the cut area?
Yes.
What were they doing?
Some were cutting but most of them they were the water people that drive around in a truck with the water and with the lunches and stuff like that.
Did you and the other guys make fun of them or anything?
No.
And were there some women at the stack area?
Yes, there were.
And they got made fun of.
They what?
They got made fun of.
They did?
But they had the cookie shack also out at the cut site.
I mean, out at the stack site.
When did you first go to muster?
Freshman year.
It was the first one in Reed Arena.
What did you think about it?
Blown away.
I remember I just, I went home and just sat by myself for like three hours after it.
I mean, I just, it was really hard to comprehend, you know.
It was great.

A year ago I did the muster, my 25th muster speech at Albuquerque and before they called the roll, a young man from Albuquerque came up and he was either a sophomore or a junior and his squad was on duty at the stack when the collapse came and his outfit, he unfurled his outfit banner which had gotten torn and there was a blood stain on it.
That was, that was touching.

Then Mrs. Curley, I was president at UT El Paso when I left here and we still have an Aggie daughter and granddaughter and grandson and a son-in-law out there and Mr. and Mrs. Curley were the I know that actually, I'm relatively close with the Curleys.
Are you?
Yeah, I am.
I'm a Fish Camp co-chair and they are namesake and so we're Camp Curley.
in there.
I haven't read it all yet.
Very, very, very touching.
Very touching.
Oh, my.
Let's see.
Muster.
Why was Muster touching?
Just because it was packed.
15,000 people were there.
For what?
Why?
I'm a big person.
I question people's motivation for stuff.
I don't question it as far as is it real or not.
But I ask the question why a lot.
I'm a big why person.
Why do you do what you do?
Why do you say what you do?
And so I was just like, okay, all these people are here.
Why?
Why are these people here?
What is the answer then?
Why were they there?
A&M.
A&M.
Why this devotion?
Something that human beings need is a sense of self within a bigger conglomerate, in my opinion.
You always need to be involved in something bigger than yourself.
I think that's why Bonfire had such a bigger feel to it because it felt like you were working not only on something now, but you were upholding something in the past.
And that's what A&M is.
A&M is believing in yourself and investing in the now to build for the future, remembering the past.
And so that is what

in my opinion muster is muster is something where you come not for yourself you're not getting anything out of that sure the muster speaker might say something where you go wow that's really cool but you're not going to learn anything about life there you go to show support for those families that are sitting on the floor you go to show support for a m you go to be there
I tell them that those words in the song, there is a spirit which can never be told.
You can't really describe it.
You can't.
You got to feel it.
You do have to feel it.
And it took some of us outsiders a while to understand that.
Now you went to some athletic events in G. Raleigh.
What was it like over there?
It was fun.
Basketball games were different.
Now no one went to basketball games my freshman year simply because we were horrible.
And see, when I left here in 1980, you couldn't get a ticket.
It was packed.
It was called the Holler House because the opposition knew that was going to be a tough place to play.
I'm so mad about athletics right now.
For you as a freshman or sophomore, what were the other key events that you and your buddies included in your calendar?
Our back porch, we had an enormous back porch at my house.
And hours upon hours upon hours were spent on the back porch playing the guitar, singing, hanging out.
Just hours.
Hanging out, that was definitely my coming to age as far as socially goes.
Just as far as going out or having friends over or staying up until dawn, just doing nothing.
Did y'all, as a little community, did you ever counsel each other?
Mm-hmm.
Oh, sure.
My roommate got engaged that week, that semester.
Actually, the spring semester myself.
Did anyone ever say to anyone else, hey, you ought not do that?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, accountability was a big part of our house.
All right.
Did you attend any religious services here?
I did.
Where?
I went to breakaway every Tuesday.
It wasn't on campus at that point.
It was still over at Central Baptist Church in Bryan.
But I went to Breakaway almost weekly.
What was special about Breakaway?
The numbers, honestly.
And the speaker, Greg Mott, I don't know if you've ever heard him or been in contact with him, but he has an amazing way of knowing what you're going through.
He has, for some reason, his thumb is on the pulse of a college student.
I can't explain it.
Some people have the gift and he's got it.
And this was on what nights?
Tuesday nights.
Tuesday nights.
All right, then on Sundays... Sundays I'd go to church.
Where?
It depended.
Sometimes I'd go to Central Baptist simply because I went to Second Baptist.
But then I'd go to Grace Bible Church as well because I...
I really, really enjoyed Dwight Edwards, who was the pastor there.
Really enjoyed his sermons because it took me like three hours to get through.
Like I'd have to go home and just ponder for a while.
So I do that.
Like one of the questions that I have here in Muskaka, were there any international events or anything like that off campus that stunned you?
No, I can't think of any, but see if it's just December 7 or, were there any international, any national catastrophes or, that you remember?
Columbine was my junior year, I think.
Do you remember where you were when you heard the news?
About Columbine?
No.
I don't.
I remember I was when Di died, Princess Di died.
It was two days before school started, I think, or it was the week before school started, my freshman year.
And I was at a fish camp party with my DG leader.
And we walked in, and the news was on, and it said, do you hear Princess Di died?
And we're like, whatever, it's just a joke.
But I totally remember that apartment.
It was in Scandi Apartments over on Anderson.
Alright, so that second, do you go out for Yale later?
As a sophomore, spring semester as a sophomore.
Describe that.
From beginning to end.
Oh, man.
Describe that.
Well, you decided to do it when?
I decided to do it Christmas break of my sophomore year just because it got to the point where I was like, okay, if I'm going to do this, then I need to do it.
And I'm the type that I don't like having questions about what ifs.
I don't like what ifs.
If you have a what if, then in my opinion, then you're not doing it right.
And so...
I'm very much a goer and a doer.
And so I was just like, okay, either I'm going to do this or I'm going to regret it for the rest of my life.
So I told my friends, I was like, okay, I'm going to run for yell leader.
And some of them were really supportive and others were just like, okay, that's really neat.
And then all the spring semester was just trying to grab a hold of this thing that is definitely not definable.
Um,
There's no handbook on how to run an election.
There's no handbook on this is how you get elected.
There's no guidelines to say this is how many people you need in each area.
This is how you do off campus.
This is how you do on campus.
This is how you budget your money.
There's no handbook on that.
It's just doing it and making sure you have the right people.
How did you do it?
I have no idea.
I look back on it.
There was a group of us, honestly.
What we did was just very radically different than anything anyone had done in the past.
We didn't focus so much on the fact that I was running for Yale leader, but on the fact that we wanted to have a relationship with every person on this campus as far as impacting people.
It was amazing, like it really was.
First campaign meeting, four people were there.
Two days before campaign started that spring break, campaign started, we had 14 people sitting in your room.
By the last day of campaigning, we had 160 people sitting in a room.
And where were these meetings?
At my house.
At your house?
They were at my house.
And what did you call it?
Did it have a...
It didn't have a...
It didn't have a name, but there was definitely something.
The color that we used was neon green.
And so we totally grabbed onto the neon green thing, both in what it meant to us.

It meant to us, I guess, joy is something you could call what my sophomore year was, simply because that's what we were trying to do, is we were trying to make people not just have a regular day of class.
We were trying to make people smile.
We handed out jokes instead of campaign materials.
We handed out little smiles, little green smiles made out of...
pipe cleaner.
And it had your name on it?
No.
They didn't even have my name on it.
The smiles didn't.
The jokes did.
But it was on the back.
We just really tried to make people happy.
We just really tried to make people smile.
We tried to make it didn't seem like it was campaigning because it wasn't campaigning.
You know, it was us having fun.
It was us going to meet people.
And I guess it was just contagious.
Now these were all civilian students in your campaign ever?
Did anybody
Did any corps group ever say anything?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
What was there?
They didn't like it.
They didn't like it.
They thought it was wrong.
They thought what I was standing for was wrong just because the corps is very not open to change.
The corps is very not open to anything that's different than the way they think.
How did y'all avoid being seen as reactionary to the corps?
It was never an issue with us, just because that wasn't my purpose for running.
My purpose for running was not to get the core.
My purpose for running was not pro non-reg.
My purpose for running is that I loved A&M, and I wanted to represent A&M at athletic events and also to everything else that Yellators do.
Did you make any speeches anywhere?
Mm-hmm.
Where?
Everywhere I could.
Everywhere I could.
I went to sororities, fraternities, SGA committees, MSC committees.
There was an open forum in the MSC where we spoke.
Anywhere I could speak, I'd speak.
And what was the substance of what you tried to convey every time?
I'd get up and talk about just the largeness of what I was running for.
Kind of give people a sense of what Yell Leader was in my mind.
And then I had a friend, actually, that would sing a song.
He had his guitar, and he would come in and sing a song that was more just fun than anything.
It was very much a campaign tactic because it was a very catchy song.
You couldn't hear the song and not have it stuck in your head for an hour.
And it was a song that we wrote.
And so it was...
I think that that's the reason I won personally.
What worked in hindsight?
What did you do that worked best and what did you do that worked least?
What worked best is I focused on individuals.
I didn't worry about organizations.
I didn't worry about the fact that the Corps was doing this.
I didn't worry about what other candidates were doing.
I worried about what the group, my friends, and the campaign staff wanted to do and we just stuck to that.
To do anything differently,
I don't know, I don't think I'd do anything differently.
And when the votes were counted, how did you, where did you?
We were at Sol Ross and I remember my friends and we were all huddled together and we made the runoff, which was just enormous.
Just because there was nine people running that year.
and we made a runoff with one of the, it was one of the guys in the Corps.
There's two?
One guy won it outright, and then I was in a runoff with the other Corps guy from Corps block.
For the one more slot?
For the one more slot.
Who led in the primary?
His name was Bubba Mosier.
No, who led?
He did.
He did.
I was behind.
I was about a thousand votes behind.
